// 02e-related-fuel-nmr — Related Work: Fuel Property Prediction from Spectroscopy

The application of spectroscopic methods to fuel property prediction has roots in the chemometrics revolution of the 1980s, when partial least squares (PLS) regression and principal component regression (PCR) were first coupled with infrared and NMR spectra to estimate hydrocarbon fuel properties. Among the earliest demonstrations was the work of Gulder @Gulder1986, who showed that proton NMR spectroscopy could predict the cetane number of diesel fuels from carbon-type structural composition determined by $""^1"H"$ spectral integration. By the mid-1990s, Fodor et al. @Fodor1996 had established a comprehensive protocol for the simultaneous determination of gasoline properties---including research and motor octane numbers, aromatic and olefinic content, and oxygenate concentrations---from a single FT-IR spectrum using multivariate calibration, achieving analysis times under one minute with less than two milliliters of sample. These foundational studies demonstrated that vibrational and magnetic resonance spectra encode sufficient molecular information to replace time-consuming wet-chemical methods, and PLS remains one of the most widely used regression techniques for fuel property prediction. The ASTM standards that define fuel quality---D1655 for aviation turbine fuel @ASTMD1655, D7566 for synthetic blending components in jet fuel @ASTMD7566, and D341 for viscosity--temperature relationships @ASTMD341\---require extensive physical testing across dozens of property specifications, creating strong incentive for rapid spectroscopic alternatives.

Near-infrared (NIR) and mid-infrared (MIR) spectroscopy have become the workhorses of online fuel quality monitoring in refineries. NIR instruments offer nondestructive, rapid analysis of parameters including density, viscosity, distillation curve, sulfur content, cold filter plugging point, and oxidation stability, making them well suited for both at-line quality control and in-line blending optimization. Baird and Oja @BairdOja2016 reviewed the chemometrics literature and extended NIR-based prediction to temperature-dependent density, achieving relative errors below one percent using support vector regression. Mid-infrared spectroscopy provides complementary information through functional-group-specific absorption features, and has been applied to diesel quality indicators with PLS models. Raman spectroscopy has emerged as a third vibrational technique for fuel characterization, offering advantages of minimal sample preparation, compatibility with aqueous environments, and analysis times as short as five seconds. Raman has proven effective for gasoline octane rating, boiling point prediction, and detection of adulterated fuels, and is now considered an emerging standard in oil, gas, and petrochemical analytical laboratories. Collectively, the vibrational spectroscopy literature establishes that multivariate regression on spectral data can approximate standard ASTM test methods, but these techniques primarily probe bulk vibrational modes and struggle to distinguish structural isomers or resolve individual carbon environments within complex hydrocarbon mixtures.

Nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy provides a uniquely atom-resolved description of molecular structure that complements the bulk functional-group information available from IR and Raman. The Clean Combustion Research Center at KAUST, led by Sarathy and Abdul Jameel, has pioneered the use of $""^1"H"$ NMR for fuel property prediction through a systematic program of publications spanning 2016--2021. Abdul Jameel et al. @AbdulJameel2016Ignition developed an improved model for derived cetane number (DCN) prediction using $""^1"H"$ NMR structural parameters---paraffinic $"CH"_3$, $"CH"_2$, and $"CH"$ groups, naphthenic $"CH"$--$"CH"_2$, olefinic $"CH"$=$"CH"_2$, and aromatic $"C"$--$"CH"$ moieties---achieving $R^2$ values of 0.97 via multiple linear regression across a diverse set of diesel fuels. Their subsequent minimalist functional group (MFG) framework @AbdulJameel2018MFG generalized this approach to surrogate fuel formulation for both diesel and jet fuels, defining a compact set of NMR-derived functional group concentrations that could reproduce ignition quality tester measurements and smoke point data. Abdul Jameel et al. @AbdulJameel2018Octane extended the approach to octane number prediction using artificial neural networks trained on NMR spectra, demonstrating that nonlinear models could capture interactions among functional groups that linear methods miss. A 2021 study @AbdulJameel2021Gasoline further refined the identification and quantification of hydrocarbon functional groups in gasoline, expanding the palette of NMR-derived descriptors available for property prediction. Kapur et al. @Kapur2003 had earlier demonstrated, independently, that neural networks could improve upon linear NMR--cetane models by capturing nonlinear structure--property relationships, anticipating the machine learning approaches that would later become standard. Cookson and Smith @Cookson1987 provided still earlier groundwork by showing that $""^(13)"C"$ NMR could resolve the saturate fraction of diesel and kerosene fuels into detailed structural categories, establishing the spectral interpretation framework on which later quantitative models were built.

The convergence of modern machine learning with spectroscopic data has accelerated fuel property prediction beyond the capabilities of classical chemometrics. Vozka and Kilaz @Vozka2020 reviewed aviation turbine fuel composition--property relations across multiple analytical platforms---NMR, IR, Raman, and gas chromatography---and concluded that spectroscopic methods consistently outperform empirical correlations when the training data span sufficient compositional diversity. Moro et al. @Moro2021 cataloged chemometric models for predicting crude oil properties from both NMR and IR spectroscopy, confirming the broad applicability of multivariate spectral regression across the petroleum value chain while noting that most published models rely on small datasets of 20--100 samples and may not generalize to novel fuel compositions. More recent work has pushed beyond PLS toward gradient-boosted trees and neural networks. Parker et al. @Parker2025DensityST demonstrated that NMR atom-type descriptors combined with XGBoost can predict liquid density and surface tension of pure hydrocarbons with accuracy rivaling group contribution methods, and that composition-weighted NMR descriptors transfer effectively to real fuel mixtures. Zipoli et al. @Zipoli2025IRNMR compiled a multimodal IR--NMR dataset of 177,000 patent-extracted organic molecules, providing the scale of training data needed for deep learning approaches to spectral property prediction.

These methodological advances address a critical bottleneck in the deployment of sustainable aviation fuels. The ASTM D4054 qualification pathway for new SAF production routes has historically required four tiers of testing spanning five or more years and costing millions of dollars @ASTMD4054. Although the Fast Track provision permits abbreviated testing for fuels compositionally similar to conventional Jet-A, blend limits are capped at ten percent, and only about eleven pathways have achieved full D7566 approval as of 2024 @Holladay2020. Heyne et al. @Heyne2021 outlined prescreening tools and procedures that use low fuel volumes to estimate critical properties early in the development process, arguing that rapid, low-cost analytical methods could dramatically reduce the time and cost of SAF qualification. The Air Force Research Laboratory maintains the most comprehensive database of jet fuel properties, documented in Edwards @Edwards2017 and the subsequent 2020 technical report @Edwards2020, covering density, viscosity, distillation, derived cetane number, surface tension, freeze point, flash point, and heat of combustion for hundreds of conventional and alternative fuels identified by POSF numbers. This database, together with complementary resources from the National Jet Fuels Combustion Program @Colket2017, provides the ground-truth measurements against which spectroscopic models must be validated.

NMR-based approaches are particularly promising for SAF screening because they provide direct, quantitative structural information---functional group distributions, branching indices, and aromatic character---that correlates physically with macroscopic thermophysical properties. Unlike IR and Raman, which primarily probe vibrational modes, NMR resolves individual carbon and hydrogen environments and can distinguish structural isomers that exhibit very different fuel performance characteristics. A branched $"C"_(12)$ isoparaffin and its linear isomer, for example, have nearly identical IR spectra but markedly different viscosities and freeze points; their $""^1"H"$ NMR spectra, by contrast, clearly resolve the methyl branching pattern. Current limitations include the capital cost of high-field NMR instrumentation and the need for larger, more diverse training sets that span the compositional space of novel SAF candidates. The development of benchtop NMR spectrometers operating at 40--80 MHz is rapidly reducing the cost barrier, bringing per-sample analysis costs to levels competitive with gas chromatography. When combined with the growing availability of large-scale spectral databases and modern machine learning architectures, NMR-based property prediction offers a path toward the rapid, low-volume fuel screening tools that the SAF qualification process urgently requires.
